SIMPLE: designation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Designation
<hw>Des`ig*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>designatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧signation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of designating; a pointing out or showing;
indication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Selection and appointment for a purpose; allotment;
direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which designates; a distinguishing mark or
name; distinctive title; appellation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The usual <qex>designation</qex> of the days of the week.</q>
<rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Use or application; import; intention;
signification, as of a word or phrase.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Finite and infinite seem . . . to be attributed primarily, in
their first <qex>designation</qex>, only to those things which have
parts.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Designative</ent>⟦br⟧
